<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-491-673  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 491 673.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 1 1990 v24 n40 p101(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Write it down! (documentation by information systems departments)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Guerrero, Carlos A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information systems professionals can benefit themselves and theircompanies by providing clear and thorough documentation of thesystems their department installs and manages.andP;  Documentationmakes the systems structure accessible to the staff of IS, and canavoid some problems that come up when a key employee leaves thestaff.andP;  Documentation can explain design idiosyncrasies caused byspecial needs for systems integration, even long after thestimulus for the design has been forgotten or changed.andP;  Using anon-narrative form of documentation, such as decision tables, canhelp pin down the logic of a design.andP;  Updates are faster andeasier with diagrams or other visual representation, and they canbe used in conjunction with other forms of documentation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information servicesDocumentationInformation SystemsMIS.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>